english:
  title: A Preface to Send Off An on His Appointment to Yangju
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yangju lies more than a hundred li from my native Gyerim. In the summer of this year, having completed my period of mourning, I was returning home when I learned that the Minister of Bamboo House had taken an official post to guard Habpo. Wishing to pay my respects, I set out, planning to lodge in Yangju on my way through Heonyang. But the heat was fierce and rain fell heavily. Those on the road warned me: "If rain falls even one more night, the Yangha River will swell, and you cannot cross for days." Since my departure deadline approached and my travel could not be delayed, I did not enter Yangju to rest, but crossed the river westward. Looking back, I saw official buildings and dwellings flickering among the dense bamboo groves—the locals pointed and said it was Yangju. Inquiring about the customs, I learned a thing or two.

    The land is narrow, the people spirited but reckless. The fields are low and marshy: in drought years the rice ripens well, but in rainy years water brings disaster. Its fortune and misfortune run opposite to other districts. Though drought does not come every year, how can heaven withhold rain perpetually from the people of one small place? Thus lean years are rare while poor harvests come in succession—such is the nature of the land. In every household, men and women alike work bamboo into implements, trading them for other goods. Their clothing and sustenance, their taxes and duties—all depend upon bamboo alone. Yet there are no great merchants or wealthy families to aid them. When traveling officials pass through, the reception is sparse, and when the district cannot manage its obligations, all vanish into the bamboo groves like startled deer and frightened foxes. Among all the southeastern districts, this one is poorest and has always been known as difficult to govern.

    When Yi Yuanyin was demoted here, he understood the affliction. First he improved the fields, deepening the irrigation channels. He had the people cultivate the abandoned lands and compensated them for their labor. Since the old customs kept people unaccustomed to farming—they went out late and returned early—he appointed supervisors for each area. He divided people into groups of ten, each group given a bamboo tablet. The first to arrive took it and passed it to the next, and so it went in turn. The last to arrive had no one to give it to, so they worked holding the tablet. When work ended, the one holding the tablet was punished with the penalty of late arrival. At that time, the minister was in the fields before dawn broke. After ten days of this, people competed to arrive first. The abandoned fields of Yangju were nearly all reclaimed, and the tablets were no longer needed.

    Before half a year passed, the minister was recalled. By then his kindness had not yet borne full fruit, and the people, old in their habits, neither sowed the cleared fields nor tended what had been planted. When I passed through Yangju, Yi had been gone barely a month. Yet I saw there how men of benevolence and virtue do not disdain humble office but lead by example in the people's work. I understood then that the poverty of Yangju's people comes not from the people alone, but from the diligence or idleness of those who govern.

    Now Bamboo House's son, Ikji, has received the command to govern Yangju. I record what I heard of Yangju and send it to encourage him: "Do not regard Yangju as small, but take up Yi's methods, and how could you fear the people cannot be governed, or their poverty cannot be made prosperity? As for the way of enriching them and then teaching them—you have already devoted yourself to this learning. Why wait for my words? The efficacy of a young scholar's reading will be seen in how the people of Yangju are transformed by your hand."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Bamboo House (竹屋) is an epithet or title for the Minister; his son Ikji (益之) is the recipient of this preface's exhortation.
  - key: ''
    value: The bamboo tablet system described here is an ingenious incentive mechanism—the threat of being publicly shamed by holding the tablet motivates workers to arrive early and work diligently.
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Yuanyin represents an ideal of virtuous governance through personal example and understanding of local conditions rather than mere administrative decree.
